Cybele, au Asiatic goddess, styled by the Greeks “the mother of the gods,'‘ was called Dindymene, srom Mount Dindymus in Phrygia. In works of art she generally appears as a grave and majestic matron. Her head is commonly crowned with towers; whence she is termed by Milton ‘⁴ the towered Cybele, mother of a hundred gods‘’ (“Arcades‚'’ v. 21). She is osten represented as roaming through the world in a chariot drawn by lions, attended by her priests, the Galli and Corybantes, who rushed about with hid- eous eries and cut themselves with knives, like the prophets of Baal (1 Kings xviii. 28). Their orgies were of a peculiarly wild and excited character, accompanied with loud music of flutes, cymbals, drums, tambourines, Sec.
